## 4. Guardrails Framework

Guardrails are implemented at **three distinct layers** — any one layer catching a violation is sufficient; no single point of failure.

### Layer 1 — Mastra Input/Output Processors (Model-level)

```typescript
// Applied to every agent turn BEFORE the LLM sees the message
inputProcessors: [
  new PromptInjectionDetector(),     // Blocks jailbreak / manipulation attempts
  new ModerationInputProcessor(),    // Filters hate speech, harassment
  new PIIDetector({                  // Detects & redacts PII in vendor's own input
    redact: false,                   // Log only — don't block (vendor is asking about their own users)
    alert: true                      // Alert if bulk PII dump detected
  }),
  new VendorScopeValidator({         // Custom: rejects if message pattern attempts cross-vendor query
    session: sessionContext
  })
]

// Applied to EVERY agent response BEFORE it reaches the vendor
outputProcessors: [
  new KYCFieldScrubber(),            // Strips any pan_number / bank_account / gst_number
                                     // from output — defense-in-depth even if tool layer leaks
  new BulkPIIDumper()                // Alerts if response contains >10 user contact records
]
```

### Layer 2 — Tool Layer (Primary Enforcement)

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                  Tool Layer Guardrails                       │
│                                                              │
│  ① Track-aware Registry Filter                               │
│     getToolsForSession(session) → only returns tools for     │
│     active_tracks; Play-only = no MRR/trial/membership tools │
│     in the tools[] array at all — model can't call them      │
│                                                              │
│  ② Server-side vendor_id Injection                          │
│     Every tool receives session_vendor_id from the           │
│     authenticated session (NOT from the model's arguments)   │
│     Model-supplied vendor IDs are ignored/overridden         │
│                                                              │
│  ③ Record Ownership Validation                              │
│     Every tool validates that the target record ID           │
│     (trial_id, booking_id, etc.) belongs to session vendor   │
│     before any read or write proceeds                        │
│                                                              │
│  ④ KYC Column Exclusion at ORM Layer                        │
│     Prisma vendorSafe() query helper never SELECTs           │
│     pan_number, bank_account.*, gst_number                   │
│     These columns don't appear in any tool's return schema   │
│                                                              │
│  ⑤ requireApproval: true on all write tools                 │
│     Mastra tool definition flag — triggers automatic         │
│     workflow suspension before any write executes            │
│                                                              │
│  ⑥ Stale Diff Re-validation                                 │
│     execute_action re-fetches current DB state before        │
│     calling portal service — if diff is stale, re-proposes  │
│     rather than silently executing on wrong data             │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Layer 3 — Audit & Observability (Detection + Alerting)

| Signal | Alert condition | Treated as |
|---|---|---|
| Cross-vendor scope rejection at tool layer | Spike (>5/min per vendor) | Security alert (possible registry/session bug) |
| `execute_action` called on non-`approved` status | Any occurrence | Critical error + page |
| `failed` executions | Spike | Ops alert |
| KYC field appearing in any tool output | Any occurrence | Critical security alert |
| Notification tool send volume | Above threshold | `requires_extra_confirmation=true` + alert |

